Create lookup tables ch2_companies, ch2_cities, ch2_job_categories and a new ch2_job_postings table with foreign keys. Migrate the existing data. Then rename 'Acme Corp' and verify all postings reflect the new name automatically.

solutions.solution:
```
CREATE TABLE ch2_companies      (id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY, name TEXT UNIQUE NOT NULL);
CREATE TABLE ch2_cities         (id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY, name TEXT UNIQUE NOT NULL);
CREATE TABLE ch2_job_categories (id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY, name TEXT UNIQUE NOT NULL);

CREATE TABLE ch2_job_postings (
  id          SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
  title       TEXT NOT NULL,
  company_id  INT REFERENCES ch2_companies(id),
  city_id     INT REFERENCES ch2_cities(id),
  category_id INT REFERENCES ch2_job_categories(id)
);

INSERT INTO ch2_companies      (name) SELECT DISTINCT company_name FROM ch2_job_postings_raw;
INSERT INTO ch2_cities         (name) SELECT DISTINCT city         FROM ch2_job_postings_raw;
INSERT INTO ch2_job_categories (name) SELECT DISTINCT category     FROM ch2_job_postings_raw;

INSERT INTO ch2_job_postings (title, company_id, city_id, category_id)
SELECT p.title, c.id, ci.id, cat.id
FROM   ch2_job_postings_raw p
JOIN   ch2_companies     c   ON c.name   = p.company_name
JOIN   ch2_cities        ci  ON ci.name  = p.city
JOIN   ch2_job_categories cat ON cat.name = p.category;

-- Rename in ONE place
UPDATE ch2_companies SET name = 'Acme Technologies' WHERE name = 'Acme Corp';
-- 1 row updated — all 5 postings reflect the new name automatically.

SELECT jp.title, c.name AS company, ci.name AS city, cat.name AS category
FROM   ch2_job_postings jp
JOIN   ch2_companies     c   ON c.id   = jp.company_id
JOIN   ch2_cities        ci  ON ci.id  = jp.city_id
JOIN   ch2_job_categories cat ON cat.id = jp.category_id;
```

Tradeoffs: reads now require JOINs. For write-heavy workloads with frequent name changes, normalization wins. For read-heavy workloads where names rarely change, a denormalized copy cached at read time can coexist with a normalized source of truth.

```
ALTER TABLE ch2_notif_relational
  ADD COLUMN priority TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT 'normal';

UPDATE ch2_notif_relational
SET    priority = 'high'
WHERE  type = 'sms';

SELECT * FROM ch2_notif_relational;
```

Good: the database now enforces that every row has a priority value. The ADD COLUMN with a DEFAULT is fast in PostgreSQL (metadata-only). Limitation: the back-fill UPDATE rewrites every SMS row. On a table with tens of millions of rows this is a slow, lock-holding operation. Tools like pg_repack or online migration frameworks (gh-ost for MySQL) exist to avoid the downtime, but they add operational complexity.

practice.description:
A package registry stores packages and their declared dependencies as a directed graph.

```
-- PostgreSQL
DROP TABLE IF EXISTS ch2_deps     CASCADE;
DROP TABLE IF EXISTS ch2_packages CASCADE;

CREATE TABLE ch2_packages (
  id      INT  PRIMARY KEY,
  name    TEXT NOT NULL,
  version TEXT NOT NULL
);

CREATE TABLE ch2_deps (
  package_id    INT REFERENCES ch2_packages(id),
  depends_on_id INT REFERENCES ch2_packages(id),
  PRIMARY KEY (package_id, depends_on_id)
);

INSERT INTO ch2_packages VALUES
  (1,'myapp','1.0.0'),(2,'webserver','2.3.1'),(3,'router','1.4.0'),
  (4,'http-lib','3.1.0'),(5,'logger','2.0.0'),(6,'utils','1.1.0'),(7,'crypto','4.2.0');

-- myapp -> webserver -> router -> http-lib
--                    -> logger  -> utils
-- myapp -> logger
-- router -> crypto
INSERT INTO ch2_deps VALUES (1,2),(1,5),(2,3),(2,5),(3,4),(3,7),(5,6);
```

Write a plain SELECT (no recursion) that returns the packages myapp directly depends on.

