Write a recursive CTE that walks the dependency graph in reverse: start from 'utils' and follow incoming edges upward.

solutions.solution:
```
UPDATE ch2_products
SET    attrs = attrs || '{"in_stock": true}'::jsonb;

INSERT INTO ch2_products (name, type, price, attrs) VALUES
  ('Refactoring', 'book', 44.99,
   '{"author": "Martin Fowler", "pages": 448,
     "isbn": "978-0-13-468599-1", "year": 2018, "in_stock": false}');

SELECT name, type, attrs->>'in_stock' AS in_stock FROM ch2_products ORDER BY name;
```

|| is the JSONB merge operator — it adds new keys and overwrites existing ones. No ALTER TABLE, no locking migration. Tradeoff: the UPDATE still rewrites every row on disk (MVCC creates new row versions), so on a large table it is not free. The advantage over ALTER TABLE is that no lock is held and reads are never blocked.

